postcontent:
I was debating on what to do for a few days.
Decided I have too many guns going into this situation so I'm selling some for the right price. That doesn't mean I'm price-gouging or selling absolutely everything on my list. Just that what I don't necessarily want to keep forever is for sale or trade for the time being while it's hassle-free.
Located in Bellingham WA - you'll probably have to come to me.

FOR SALE/TRADE:
Various AK-47 types and configurations
Bolt action Type-53 Mosin, standard spec but refinished wood. 
.44 Magnum Desert Eagle w/ Hogue finger grips, case, Eagle branded shoulder holster and 5 standard mags. Very accurate and doesn't jam with good ammo (I've heard that's the case with most of them, if they jam people are using garbage underpowered ammo.)
Taurus PT92 9mm with one standard mag, one 32rd mag, police style black fobus Safariland holster.
Bernardelli P-One 9mm, 1 mag. Very smooth and comfortable gun.
CZ-52 in one of my favorite calibers, 7.62x25, which is making a come-back with commercial ammo out and sure to come down in price to be more in line with 9mm soon. 2 mags and holster.
Bolt action 16ga holds 5+1 without block in it. I got it with a piece of wood that fits inside the spring and plugs it to 2+1. Can include that if someone wants it for hunting rather than home-D.
Full-size 1911 (Shooter's Arms Chief which is a non-standard frame style with a finger groove and squared trigger guard) with quick release paddle style holster, extended ambidextrous slide release, muzzle brake, 10rd extended mag and 2 8-rd mags, plastic under-grip mag-well attachment.
Mosin revolver with lots of gold accents.

All guns are black/black finish/black plastic with wood, silver or gold accents. Pics on specific gun request.
I have ammo for everything and could release some or all of it with each sale.

WILL TRADE FOR:
Anything interesting, specifically mid to high caliber Semi-auto rifles and pistols.
I'm not a huge fan of bolt-actions, collectibles or most shotguns. I am big on military, police or government / agent surplus.
Pistols:
I want a Jericho / Uzi Eagle / Baby Eagle pistol in any caliber. Steel frame only, I don't like the new polymer versions.
I wouldn't mind a .40 or .45 CZ / Witness / Tanfoglio / EAA / TZ or an odd off-brands from Turkey or anywhere else so long as they're nice looking, working and high-cap.
9mm or .22 Sig / Beretta or other pistols with threaded muzzles.
I also want something with some extra power for fun. .50 AE DE (or barrel/mag combo or trade a .50 for my .44) or maybe a .357 snub-nose revolver or a .44 midsize revolver. I like the EAA Windicator - a similar style would be nice.

Rifles:
Maybe a FAL / L1A1 / IMBEL .308 type of semi-auto.
I like the old French MAS style guns and if someone has one they don't want to keep long-term I might be interested in one of those also. 
I want a long-barreled (pref. hex receiver) Mosin rifle as well but it must have a nice bore.

Possibly a 12ga shotgun... I'd just have to see it to know if I like it.

title: For Sale:  Ruger MK (Mark) II .22 Cal. Long Rifle
location: Coachella Valley, East Riverside County, Inland Empire, California
postcontent:
Update (see new photos): I just finished completely rebuilding this Ruger MK II .22 caliber handgun once again, including a new trigger assembly, a new casing extractor, extractor plunger, and plunger spring, along with a new mainspring, firing pin, and firing pin recoil spring. The entire unit has been rebuilt, recalibrated, and retested, including sighting it in. It is now more accurate and smoother in its action and working than ever, along with essentially no recoil whatsoever.

It now works so well that it is better than almost any entries, new or old, in the same class, that I have seen or tried myself. It is extremely well balanced when empty, but even better when it has a magazine loaded. I have tried many of the newer offers in the same class at local, and/or out-of-state ranges, but I must say that I prefer this weapon over all of the others. Once you have seen the accuracy for yourself, you will agree. Even when firing this weapon cold, it was easier to handle, felt better balanced, and was far more accurate--which is what you would want in an emergency situation, as with an intruder--than any other model that I have recently fired. If I did not need the money, I would never sell this weapon. However, I do need the money, and so here it is.

Anyhow, more about the update on this weapon. There are other new or reconditioned parts that I installed or rebuilt (or re-milled) on this model, but suffice it to say that essentially this is a brand new weapon as far as the insides go, how well it works, and for how long it will last with all of the new heat-forged parts installed, instead of the stamped parts that the manufacturer puts in at the factory, or that were subsequently installed during the life of this model by the revious owner. It is an absolutely beautiful range weapon, with target groupings that are better than some long rifles that I have used. If you know how to shoot with a handgun, then the accuracy is unquestionsble, as you will be able to see for yourself once you get it to a range.

Speaking of which, not only is it accurate as hell, but it does an enormous amount of damage for a small caliber weapon with the included CCI Mini Mag hollow-point 36 Gr. rounds. These rounds, with their high velocity and hollow points, actually do more damage than many larger rounds in higher caliber weapons that I have used. Additionally, the ammunition is inexpensive. Because of all of the rebuilding, as well as all of the new parts, I am now asking $325 for this model. It is worth every penny in my opinion.
 **END UPDATE**

This handgun is, as noted on the barrel, a Sturm, Ruger, & Co., Inc., Southport, Conn. U.S.A., Ruger MK II .22 Cal. Long Rifle semi-automatic pistol. This handgun comes with three factory-made, 10-round, Ruger magazines, with the Ruger emblem located on the base of each, to match the Ruger emblem located on the original, factory grips. The serial number is: 212-58XXX, meaning that this pistol was manufactured in 1986 (see below). I also have the original owner's manual in PDF form for emailing to a prospective buyer, or to the person who actually purchases this handgun.

When I first purchased this pistol off of the previous owner, I completely overhauled it. The parts now all fit nice and tight, and the barrel and action were completely disassembled, cleaned, reconditioned, and put back together with loving care. This pistol has the best groupings on the range of any of my other handguns, so it indeed has retained (and regained, as I felt when testing the fully restored weapon) its accuracy. It has had around 200 rounds put down the barrel since I finished the restoration, so it is in great shape still. The bluing is a little worn in a few spots, mostly due to the Rip-Stop Nylon holster in which it was stored. The holster was a bit abrasive right over the serial number/breech area of this pistol, but otherwise, the bluing is intact and looks decent. There are a few minor scratches from wear and tear, including a small one where the automatic breech lock safety rubbed a bit against the frame. I have since straightened out the safety, so the scratch will not worsen.

So overall, this is a very nice handgun to add to one's collection, or a great target or range pistol if accuracy is important to you. It shoots straight, it shoots great, and it is shiny and clean, and the parts are tight in all the right places. All in all, this is a very nice handgun, including the three, 10-round magazines, and a 100-round box of new, hollow point, CCI Mini Mags. The box in the pictures looks a bit worn, but that is from being stored in my range bag. 

However, I treat my ammunition as I do my weapons: that is, I clean and polish every round by hand. So rest assured that the ammunition inside of the box is in top notch condition. The cleaner the ammunition, the cleaner your weapon will stay, and the less wear and tear will be accrued over the lifetime of said weapon: the less gunk and oxidization that come into contact with the weapon's parts via dirty rounds or even slightly oxidized casings, the less overall wear and tear and the fewer chemical reactions there are to degrade the weapon. That is my philosophy, and it has proved true over the years. My weapons are cleaner, and last longer, than many other models of the same age and with the same usage.

title: For Sale:  Concealed Weapons Permit Class (aka Concealed Carry Course) for $59
postcontent:
One of the requirements by the State of Florida to apply for a concealed weapons permit is to have successfully taken a concealed carry course under a certified instructor. Miami Shooters Club provides such a course with its team of NRA certified instructors - who will teach students the important fundamentals of how to safely use a semi-automatic pistol and revolver. Your concealed weapons permit will allow you to concealed carry in more than 30 states.

Miami Shooters Club's instructors carry multiple certifications under the NRA, have traveled abroad to train and receive firearm certifications, and are hand-to-hand self defense experts - having taught multiple seminars for the Miami Dade Police Department. Under their instruction in the concealed carry class, students will learn the mechanisms behind pistols and how they operate while learning how to grip the firearm, aim, pull the trigger, get into a proper stance, and much more. The class also covers many of the legal issues and expected ethics of concealed carry in Florida. The classes are designed for complete beginners who have never touched a gun before... but experienced shooters will learn something as well.

At the end of the classroom portion, students will safely discharge a pistol under the supervision of a certified instructor, as required by the State of Florida. Miami Shooters Club will provide a firearm, ammunition, eye protection, and ear protection at no extra cost.

Classes take place in Miami on Fridays at 6:30pm or on Saturdays at 1pm.

Call now at REDACTED or send an email to REDACTED with your name and phone number for more information.
